node.text:
This Saturday, Hope Run, the film about my 50 mile run through the land formerly protected as the Bears Ears National Monument will have its world premiere at the Forward Motion Fest (a production of @trailfilmfest).

The Trail Running Film Festival is donating 10% of  TODAY'S ticket sales to their virtual show this Saturday to support the Bears Ears Intertribal Coalition. Get your tickets NOW at www.trailfilmfest.com. 

I’m honestly so humbled to have a film about my run play at this festival. Running is hard and I still have so much to learn! I’m grateful to be able to share the experience of my 50 miler through this film - the highs and the lows! Huge thanks to @rob.lea for crewing and filming. @michellescreative for editing and working together and @patagonia_trailrunning and @clifbar for their support.

node.text:
The climate crisis is one of those things that can feel so overwhelming, like there’s nothing I can do. But there’s so much you can do if you’re creative. Getting some of my friends together, designing a challenge, and doing a fundraising for a local, environmental non profit, is one of many ways you can engage and create meaningful change. 

I'm so excited to share my latest film, 29,032', that chronicles my journey to climb up and ski down the vertical relief of Everest/Chomolungma in a single day for my @protectourwinters #Crushit4Climate and @upforairseries fundraiser for @utahcleanenergy. Together, we raised over $10K to bring more clean, renewable energy to Utah which was matched by a @patagonia grant for $10K ($20K total!!!) 

Huge thanks to @brightonresort for their commitment to renewable energy and for allowing me to climb up and ski down at the resort, to @zachcoury for filming, to @dkcarty12 for filming and editing and to @marykmcintyre for the photos. And an enormous thank you to everyone who supported! 

#everesting #29032 #skimo #cleanenergy #climatecrisis

node.text:
Can you remove your skins without taking your skis off? 

When I’m backcountry skiing, I like to have a series of steps in place that I do the same way everytime. For transitioning from skinning to skiing, I think of it as a 3-step process that I repeat on both sides. First, I adjust my boots, Then, my bindings, putting the toe from skin to ski mode, then adjusting the heel piece. Finally, I rip my skins. Then, I repeat on the other side. 

Note: this works best with a simple binding and boot, like the @plum_officiel Oazo 6 or Race 170 and the @scarpana Alien or F1 boots. Make sure you have powder baskets on your poles. It helps to keep skis waxed!

node.text:
I used to struggle so much when it came time to put skins on, so I thought I’d share a couple tricks I've learned to help you when putting skins on or going from skiing back to skinning.

When it’s time to transition, I begin by stomping out a few steps in the snow on my skis. Then, I only take off one ski at a time, so I have a nice platform and I don’t sink into the snow. Instead of pulling apart my skins, I hook the loop of my skin on to the tip of my ski and start pulling gently to get a nice adhesion. I clear the snow off my ski and pull it the rest of the way apart. I push the tail of my ski against my ski boot for leverage to pull my skin apart (this is much easier with a flat tailed ski instead of a twin tip). 

When you’re making a lot of backcountry laps, you want to take care to avoid getting snow on your skins when transitioning. After doing one ski, I put that ski back on and then repeat the process on the other ski.

Be sure to check the avalanche forecast before heading into the backcountry, carry the appropriate rescue gear and have the training to manage avalanche risk.

node.text:
Six years ago today, one of my best friends, @liz_daley, was killed in an avalanche in Patagonia. Liz was a huge inspiration in my life because she was one of the first women I met who showed me that you can be feminine, strong, assertive and still wear glittery nail polish or pink and purple. She was a skilled mountaineer, splitboarder and loyal friend. Before meeting her, I didn't know anyone who was so openly feminine and such a ripper in the mountains. She gave me an example of who I wanted to become, and I spent years building my mountaineering skills so I could be a competent partner for the goals we shared. Even though it's been six years, it still feels like a giant hole in my heart. 
AK Girls Way is a short video from the last trip we did together. It was the culmination a few years of planning. I learned so much on that trip.
Remembering Liz today puts some energy back into my fight for creating an outdoor industry that is inclusive and where people can see themselves represented. Let's never forget you can be a girly girl, wear sparkles and be strong, powerful and aggressive. Let's continue to create a world where people are free to be the best versions of themselves. You can celebrate Liz's memory with me by making a donation to the @lizrocksfoundation.
Film: Jason Thompson
@patagonia_snow @lekiusa @clifbar @prethelmets @jaybeyerimaging

I had so much fun getting dressed up and attending the @nuzzlesandco fundraising gala this past Saturday! @lilarbg was the cutest date and was featured in a short video at the gala (hoping to repost soon). 

If you’re looking for a pet in Park City or Salt Lake City, or if you’re interested in fostering, I highly recommend connecting with the folks at Nuzzles. Utah is getting very close to becoming a no-kill state (we will likely make it within the next year)! But it’s going to take work to keep it that way. I’m a proud foster failure from Nuzzles! Thanks to my friend @bethskis for introducing me to Nuzzles and to all the staff and volunteers who are saving animals. ❤️❤️❤️#adoptdontshop #nuzzlesalumni

Yesterday, I teamed up a group of fellow @protectourwinters athletes and friends to meet with @agardiner, Senator @mittromney’s State Director, to share our concerns about the climate crisis and to advocate for climate action now in the infrastructure package and beyond. I want to give a huge thank you to Adam for taking the time to meet with us today, and spending an entire hour with us on his wife’s birthday! And to our crew! 

Today was the first in-person meeting I’ve had almost 18 months and I’ve really missed seeing and being with people in real life. Activism is way more fun with friends! #ActOnClimate

node.text:
I’ve started using “climate emergency” or “climate crisis” instead of “climate change” to communicate the severity of the issue (thanks for the nudge on that @mollykawahata). This weekend, we have another excessive heat warming across Utah, coupled with unhealthy air quality from wildfires in the West. Excessive heat doesn’t just make ridge running more uncomfortable: it’s deadly. In the Pacific Northwest, the recent heat wave resulted in hundreds of deaths.

What we are seeing is what climate scientists have predicted for decades. We have put a pollution blanket around the earth which traps heat, melts ice, raises sea levels, and makes storms, wildfires and droughts much stronger. 

99% of scientists agree that humans are heating our planet with carbon pollution, threatening our health, safety, economy and security. 

The good news is, we know how to remove the pollution blanket: by stopping pollution and switching to clean energy.

Clean energy is not only healthier, it’s now cheaper than polluting energy. For more info on how to communicate about the climate crisis, check out the link in my profile for the article, “Language to Win on Climate.” 

I’ve been super focused lately on both climate crisis communications and training for trail running. 

Photo: not today. Ridge running a few years ago by @rob.lea

node.text:
Running the Jupiter Peak Steeplechase course was a huge highlight of my weekend! At almost 17 miles with 3400’ of climbing, it was my longest run of 2021! I’m stoked to be settling back into running. It always takes my skier legs a few weeks to adapt to the faster turnover. 

I learned that the Jupiter Peak Steeplechase has been happening for almost 30 years; it’s a good test piece for mountain runners. It’s a virtual race this year so the course is marked from now until July 17. I slept in and started mid morning which allowed me to get some good heat training in as well! My @savethebwca bandana kept me cool(ish). I really enjoyed going solo and self-supported this time. I love runs with friends too but going alone allows me to move to my own rhythm and breath and really listen to my body. 

@julboeyewearna @patagonia_trailrunning 

Thanks @mtntrailspc for the well-marked course!
On Núu-agha-tʉvʉ-pʉ̱ (Ute) and Eastern Shoshone land.

node.text:
Skiing Iceland’s highest peak, Hvannadalshnúkur, Part 2. 

I was determined to ski in Iceland and I was watching the weather like a hawk, waiting for any weather window. I’ve skied on other islands before and they are notorious for their unpredictable weather. I saw one clear day on the radar, and as we got closer to that day, I gained more and more confidence that we’d have the right weather conditions to go up Hvannadalshnúkur. Two days before, we drove down from the Westfjords to the southeast part of the island to get into position for the summit day. 

It had been a minute since we’d roped up to travel in glaciated, crevassed terrain. We watched some last minute refreshers online to prepare the night before. 

We were able to keep skis and skins on all the way to the top. 

The route has a 1.5 mile section before the last pitch summit that is flat as a pancake! There were some crevasses to navigate around on the final pitch to the summit. After a quick break at the top, it was time to drop in. We had a few steep turns, then the long, 1.5 mile slog that we were able to skate ski on the return. 

Then, miles and miles of 20-30° skiing in a few centimeters of fresh pow. It was dreamy and delightful to ski a big mountain in a new to me mountain range! Thanks @rob.lea for being my adventure buddy! 
@elanskis @julboeyewearna @lekiusa @clifbar @patagonia_snow

Skiing Hvannadalshnúkur, Iceland’s highest peak: Part 1. 

Iceland’s highest peak is actually a point on the rim of a giant crater on the Öræfajökull volcano. It is on the Vatnajökull glacier, which is the largest ice cap in Europe and covers 8% of Iceland. The glaciers here are in the warmest and wettest area in Iceland and respond quickly to changes in temperature and precipitation, which is why climate scientists are using them to research the relationship between glaciers and climate change. 

I bought a cool book about Icelandic climate research in this region at the tourist shop and wanted to share some facts from it. 

The glaciers have now retreated 1-6km, depending on their location, since the end of the little ice age. 

Since 2000, the outlet glaciers have retreated very fast and their mass loss per unit are is among the highest in the world. The amount of ice lost corresponds to a .33mm rise in global sea level. If Icelandic ice caps lost all of their ice, it would raise the sea level by 1cm. 

As glaciers retreat, they become more dangerous for mountaineers. When permafrost melts, mountain slopes become unstable and landslides and rock avalanches are triggered. Landslides into glacial lakes can trigger sudden flood waves or tsunamis that pose a hazard to people and public infrastructure. 

Models indicate that after 200 years there will only be small icecaps left on the highest mountains. 

Stay tuned for more in parts 2 and 3! 

I apologize to any Icelandic speaking folks who listen to this because our pronunciation of the peak’s name leaves room for improvement. 

@elanskis @lekiusa @julboeyewearna @patagonia_snow @clifbar #alwaysgoodtimes #feedyouradventure #bigmtndreams #climatecrisis

Thanks @rob.lea for filming!

node.text:
Two weeks in Iceland in 30s. 

Before this trip, I was on the verge of burnout. At the beginning of the pandemic, I lost a few big jobs. I was so afraid I would lose all my work, I began panic working and saying yes to every opportunity that came up. The months went by, but I could never seem to relax. The same thing was happening to my partner. 
 
We decided we needed a vacation. After learning that Iceland was open to vaccinated tourists, we booked plane tickets one week out. We booked a rental car, the first night of lodging and we decided to go for it, planning as we went along. And I’m so glad we did. Here’s a quick video montage of some of the moments!
 
I learned that my best work comes from a place of love, joy and fulfillment, not stress. I am partnering with @backcountry to encourage you to get outside and explore new zones to keep the stoke alive! 

Check out my stories to see some of my favorite travel items from the trip to Iceland and use code CAROLINE15 for 15% off your first purchase at backcountry.com (some exclusions apply). #findyourbackcountry #sponsored

node.text:
Feeling the power of the water and cool mist was invigorating as I walked right up to the edge of Skógafoss, one of the highest waterfalls in Iceland (almost 200ft/60m high). 

Coming from arid Utah, I loved all the water in Iceland. Clean air and water are precious resources that every traveler values! 

Thanks as always for filming @rob.lea!

node.text:
Happy Father’s Day to the dads out there! To honor and celebrate my dad and explore my own thoughts about parenthood, I wrote a story for @patagonia’s blog, The Cleanest Line called “Jerry’s Wisdom.” It’s about the pressure I feel to have children and the wisdom from my dad I would want my kids to know. Relationships with our dads can be complicated and awesome at the same time. Check it out via the link in my profile. 

Thanks @leecohen_pics for the shots with my dad.

node.text: I’ve been involved in the photo world for almost two decades, on both sides of the lens, chasing perfect light and waking up at all hours of the day to “get the shot.” I’m really excited to share these photos @rob.lea and I captured on the final moments of our Iceland trip! Iceland’s weather presents an interesting challenge, but when the light comes out, it’s unbelievable. And that evening light combined with the power of the volcano and the bright, red lava...I can’t wait to share more of our photos from the trip!
